1 WHEREAS, the state may benefit from evaluating whether Louisiana One Call and
2 related 811 coordination functions should be incorporated into a dedicated division, office,
3 or enhanced state structure to improve oversight, coordination, data sharing, enforcement,
4 training, and long-term planning; and
5 WHEREAS, a study could help identify opportunities for improved efficiency,
6 enhanced protection of underground infrastructure, better coordination between state and
7 local entities, and potential integration with broadband deployment and utility mapping
8 initiatives.
9 THEREFORE, BE IT RESOLVED that the House of Representatives of the
10 Legislature of Louisiana does hereby urge and request the Public Service Commission to
11 study the feasibility and advisability of incorporating Louisiana One Call and 811-related
12 functions into a dedicated state division, office, or administrative structure.
13 BE IT FURTHER RESOLVED that the Public Service Commission shall coordinate
14 with and receive input from the following entities to assist in the study:
15 (1) The Department of Transportation and Development.
16 (2) The office of broadband, development and connectivity.
17 (3) Louisiana One Call.
18 (4) Utility providers.
19 (5) Local governments.
20 (6) Other relevant stakeholders.
21 BE IT FURTHER RESOLVED that the study shall include but not be limited to the
22 following:
23 (1) The current structure, governance, and funding of Louisiana One Call and the
24 811 system.
25 (2) The feasibility of creating a dedicated division or office focused on underground
26 utility coordination, damage prevention, utility mapping, and excavation safety.
27 (3) Potential improvements in coordination between utilities, excavators, state
28 agencies, local governments, and broadband providers.
29 (4) Opportunities for enhanced enforcement, data collection, reporting, and
30 accountability related to underground utility damages.
